  "text": "[Skip to content](https://tinytotintokyo.com/tokyo-family-events#main)\n[![Tiny Tot In Tokyo](https://tinytotintokyo.com/tokyo-family-events)![Tiny Tot In Tokyo](https://tinytotintokyo.com/tokyo-family-events)](https://tinytotintokyo.com/)\n  * [Home](https://tinytotintokyo.com/)\n  * [Japan LifeExpand](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life)\n    * [General](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/general-2)\n    * [Trying to Conceive](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/trying-to-conceive)\n    * [PregnancyExpand](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/pregnancy)\n      * [Labor/Birth](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/pregnancy/labor-birth)\n      * [First Trimester](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/pregnancy/first-trimester)\n      * [Second Trimester](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/pregnancy/second-trimester)\n      * [Third Trimester](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/pregnancy/third-trimester)\n      * [Birth Stories](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/pregnancy/interviews)\n      * [Products](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/products)\n      * [Reviews](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/reviews)\n      * [General](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/pregnancy/general)\n    * [BabyExpand](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/baby)\n      * [Newborn](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/baby/newborn)\n      * [First Year](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/baby/first-year)\n      * [Second Year](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/baby/second-year)\n      * [Food](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/baby/food)\n      * [Daycare](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/baby/daycare)\n      * [Japanese Traditions](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/baby/japanese-traditions)\n      * [Places to Go](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/baby/places-to-go)\n      * [Product Reviews](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/baby/product-reviews)\n      * [Recipes](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/baby/recipes-baby)\n      * [Songs](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/baby/songs)\n      * [General](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/baby/baby-baby)\n    * [ToddlerExpand](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/toddler)\n      * [Food](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/toddler/food-toddler)\n      * [Recipes](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/toddler/food-toddler/recipes-food-toddler)\n      * [Yochien (Preschool)](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/toddler/yochien-preschool)\n    * [Kids](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/kids)\n    * [Books](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/books)\n    * [Events](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-life/events)\n  * [Japan TravelExpand](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-travel)\n    * [Tokyo](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-travel/tokyo)\n    * [Osaka](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-travel/osaka)\n    * [Japan-wide](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-travel/japan-wide)\n    * [Kansai Region](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-travel/kansai-region)\n    * [Kanto Region](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-travel/kanto-region)\n    * [Hokkaido Region](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-travel/hokkaido-region)\n    * [Shikoku Region](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-travel/shikoku-region)\n    * [Hyogo](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-travel/hyogo)\n    * [Kyoto](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-travel/kyoto)\n    * [Nara](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-travel/nara)\n    * [Wakayama](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-travel/wakayama)\n    * [Okinawa](https://tinytotintokyo.com/category/japan-travel/okinawa)\n  * [AboutExpand](https://tinytotintokyo.com/about-me)\n    * [About Me](https://tinytotintokyo.com/about-me)\n    * [Privacy Policy](https://tinytotintokyo.com/privacy-policy)\n    * [Subscription Form](https://tinytotintokyo.com/subscription)\n    * [Contact](https://tinytotintokyo.com/contact)\n\n\nSearch\n[Instagram](https://www.instagram.com/tinytotintokyo/)\n[![Tiny Tot In Tokyo](https://tinytotintokyo.com/tokyo-family-events)![Tiny Tot In Tokyo](https://tinytotintokyo.com/tokyo-family-events)](https://tinytotintokyo.com/)\nSearch\n[Instagram](https://www.instagram.com/tinytotintokyo/)\nToggle Menu\n# Best Family-Friendly Events in Tokyo (2026)\n![Tokyo's cityscape with the text \"Tokyo Family Events\"](https://tinytotintokyo.com/tokyo-family-events)\nLast Updated on April 17, 2026 by [Kay](https://tinytotintokyo.com/about-me)\nThis post may contain affiliate links, meaning I may earn a small commission on any purchases through those links at zero additional cost to you. Whatever I make goes to keeping this website running and I am forever grateful for the support. See [my Privacy Policy](https://tinytotintokyo.com/privacy-policy) for more information.\nLooking for fun family events in Tokyo worth adding to your plans?\nUnsurprisingly, Tokyo is packed with things to do with kids, whether you’re entertaining a curious toddler, a curious preschooler, or energetic older children who are ready for something new and exciting. There’s always something new popping up, from seasonal events and interactive exhibits to weekend activities the whole family can enjoy.\nAs a mom living in Japan, I’ve pulled together my personal picks for the best upcoming family-friendly events in Tokyo so you can spend less time searching and more time planning a day out.\nDo keep in mind that dates, times, and details can change, so it’s always worth checking the official website before you go, especially since some events require you to purchase tickets in advance.\nNote that these events can also be quite packed with visitors, particularly with one or two-day events, and on weekends and holidays.\n## Tokyo Family-Friendly Events for Kids in 2026\n### DINO SAFARI 2026\nDates: April 24, 2026 – May 6, 2026\nThis dinosaur-themed event looks like a fun pick for families with kids who enjoy lifelike prehistoric creatures and immersive experiences.\n_🎟️ Advance ticket purchase is required_\n[🔗 See event details here](https://dinosafari.jp/)\n### Ice Cream Expo Premium TOKYO 2026\nDates: April 24, 2026 – May 6, 2026\nThis popular gourmet event brings together a wide range of ice cream and frozen treats, making it a fun stop for families with a sweet tooth.\n_🎟️ Advance ticket purchase is recommended_\n[🔗 See event details here](https://www.i-89.jp/)\n### Tenbou Park Sakura Festival\nDates: February 26, 2026 – May 10, 2026\nThis seasonal event at Sunshine 60 Observatory combines cherry blossom-themed displays with workshops and indoor family fun.\n_🎟️ Advance ticket purchase is recommended_\n[🔗 See event details here](https://sunshinecity.jp/observatory/event/entry-36300.html)\n### Thrilling Deep-Sea Creatures\nDates: January 16, 2026 – May 10, 2026\nThis special aquarium event at [Sunshine City](https://tinytotintokyo.com/sunshine-city-ikebukuro-with-kids) focuses on mysterious deep-sea life and looks like a good option for kiddos (like mine) who enjoy unusual marine creatures.\n_🎟️ Advance ticket purchase is recommended_\n[🔗 See event details here](https://sunshinecity.jp/file/aquarium/zokuzoku_deep_sea/)\n### Flower Festival 2026\nDates: March 20, 2026 – May 24, 2026\nThis spring flower festival at Showa Kinen Park is a lovely choice for families who want to enjoy seasonal blooms and open-air walks.\n[🔗 See event details here](https://www.showakinen-koen.jp/flower-festival/)\n### Jurassic Maze at Yomiuriland Dinosaur Laboratory\nDates: March 20, 2026 – May 25, 2026\nThis dinosaur-themed maze adds an adventurous twist to a day at Yomiuriland and should appeal to kids who love prehistoric creatures.\n_🎟️ Advance ticket purchase is recommended_\n[🔗 See event details here](https://www.yomiuriland.com/sp/2026/dinosaur/)\n### Harapeko Spring\nDates: March 1, 2026 – May 31, 2026\nThis spring event at PLAY! PARK ERIC CARLE features hands-on activities and playful experiences that seem especially suited for toddlers.\n_🎟️ Advance ticket purchase is recommended_\n[🔗 See event details here](https://playec.jp/news/event/harapekospring_2026/)\n### Mundo Pixar: Pixar World Exhibition\nDates: March 20, 2026 – May 31, 2026\nThis immersive Pixar-themed exhibition is a fun option for families who enjoy Disney and interactive character experiences.\n_🎟️ Advance ticket purchase is required_\n[🔗 See event details here](https://mundopixar.com)\n### MIDTOWN OPEN THE PARK 2026\nDates: April 24, 2026 – May 31, 2026\nThis seasonal outdoor event at Tokyo Midtown features open-air activities and workshops, making it a nice choice for spring in the city.\n[🔗 See event details here](https://www.tokyo-midtown.com/jp/news/7934/)\n### Tokyo Skytree Town Koinobori Festival 2026\nDates: April 10, 2026 – May 6, 2026\nThis seasonal event celebrates Children’s Day with around 1,000 koinobori displayed across Tokyo Skytree Town, creating a colorful and very photogenic atmosphere.\n[🔗 See event details here](https://www.tokyo-solamachi.jp/event/2456/)\n### Orb: On the Movement of the Earth × Tokyo City View\nDates: April 10, 2026 – June 8, 2026\nThis special collaboration event combines the observatory setting with themed content inspired by the anime and manga Orb: _On the Movement of the Earth_ , making it a unique pick for kids and teens who are fans of the series.\n[🔗 See event details here](https://tcv.roppongihills.com/jp/exhibitions/chi-event/)\n### Extremely Dangerous Creatures Exhibition: The True Power of Animals Through Science\nDates: March 14, 2026 – June 14, 2026\nThis science-focused exhibition explores dangerous creatures from a research perspective and looks like a strong option for families with school-age kids.\n[🔗 See event details here](https://chokikenseibutsuten.jp/)\n### Sanrio Exhibition: The Beginning of Kawaii (Final)\nDates: April 9, 2026 – June 21, 2026\nThis special Sanrio exhibition featuring Hello Kitty is for fans of all ages, with displays centered around the world of Sanrio and its long history. Note that there isn’t much that’s interactive here, so it’s more look but not touch (which can be boring for kids).\n_🎟️ Advance ticket purchase is required_\n[🔗 See event details here](https://tokyofinalexhibition.com/)\n### Detective Conan Cafe\nDates: April 10, 2026 – May 17, 2026; May 20, 2026 – August 2, 2026\nThis limited-time themed café has a nostalgic “port town retro” concept, with character-themed food, drinks, and exclusive goods. It is a strong option for Conan fans and for families with older kids who enjoy the series.\n_🎟️ Advance ticket purchase is recommended_\n[🔗 See event details here](https://conan-cafe.jp/)\n### Design Festa\nDates: May 23, 2026 – May 24, 2026\nThis is a personal favorite event of mine. I don’t think it’s very good for babies or toddlers, but creative and curious preschoolers and older kids (like my daughter) will likely love it.\nThis huge art and design event brings together original creators, live painting, performances, workshops, and food, making it a fun choice for families with creative kids and teens.\n_🎟️ Advance ticket purchase is recommended_\n[🔗 See event details here](https://designfesta.com/)\n### Sanja Matsuri\nDates: May 15, 2026 – May 17, 2026\nOne of Tokyo’s most famous traditional festivals, Sanja Matsuri fills Asakusa with parades, mikoshi processions, and festival energy. It can be exciting for families, though it is usually very crowded.\n[🔗 See event details here](https://asakusajinja.jp/sanjamatsuri/schedule/)\n### The 50th JAPAN HOBBY SHOW 2026\nDates: May 8, 2026 – May 10, 2026\nThis large hobby and handmade event features crafts, DIY, art, and creative displays, and workshops for kids, making it great for families with children (like mine) who enjoy making things.\n_🎟️ Advance ticket purchase is recommended_\n[🔗 See event details here](https://2026.hobbyshow.jp/about)\n### Adachi Fireworks\nDates: May 30, 2026\nThis early-summer fireworks event is one of Tokyo’s big seasonal highlights and can be a memorable choice for families who want a classic local festival atmosphere.\n[🔗 See event details here](https://www.city.adachi.tokyo.jp/hodo/topics/2026fireworks.html)\n### Bunkyo Hydrangea Festival (Ajisai Matsuri)\nDates: June 2026  \nThe official 2026 schedule has not been announced yet.\nHeld around Hakusan Shrine and Hakusan Park, this hydrangea festival is known for its beautiful rainy-season flowers and neighborhood feel, making it a chill, lower-key outing for families.\n[🔗 See event details here](https://b-kanko.jp/festival)\n### Shitamachi Tanabata Matsuri\nDates: July 2026  \nThe official 2026 dates have not been announced yet.\nThis colorful Tanabata festival is held along Kappabashi Hondori and is known for its bamboo decorations, parade atmosphere, and family-friendly summer street-festival feel.\n[🔗 See event details here](https://www.city.taito.lg.jp/event/kanko/shitamathitanabata.html)\n### Kagurazaka Matsuri\nDates: July 2026  \nThe official 2026 event page appears to be in preparation, but detailed dates are not posted yet.\nThis summer festival is usually one of Kagurazaka’s seasonal highlights, with a mix of neighborhood atmosphere, hozuki market elements, and Awa Odori performances.\n[🔗 See event details here](https://www.kagurazaka.in/)\n### Sumida River Fireworks Festival\nDates: July 25, 2026\nOne of Tokyo’s most famous fireworks events, this riverside display is a major summer tradition and a great pick for families who want a classic Tokyo matsuri atmosphere.\n[🔗 See event details here](https://www.sumidagawa-hanabi.com/about/)\n### Tokyo Koenji Awa Odori\nDates: August 29, 2026 – August 30, 2026\nThis lively dance festival fills the Koenji area with music, movement, and summer energy, and it can be especially fun for families who enjoy traditional performances in a festive street setting.\n[🔗 See event details here](https://www.koenji-awaodori.com/about/about01.html)\n### Harajuku Omotesando Genki Matsuri Super Yosakoi\nDates: August 29, 2026 – August 30, 2026\nThis high-energy yosakoi festival brings colorful dance teams to Harajuku, Omotesando, Yoyogi Park, and nearby areas, making it a fun late-summer event for families who enjoy live performances.\n[🔗 See event details here](https://www.super-yosakoi.tokyo/outline/)\n[_Looking for more things to do in Tokyo with kids?_](https://tinytotintokyo.com/best-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids-and-day-trips)\nPlease leave this field empty\n**JOIN THE MAILING LIST**\n![](https://tinytotintokyo.com/tokyo-family-events)\nAs a small token of my appreciation, I'll also send you a FREE Japanese and English printable to help your little one learn all about words associated with spring in Japan 🌸\nThis field is required.\nCheck your inbox or spam folder to confirm your subscription.\nPlease leave this field empty\n![](https://tinytotintokyo.com/tokyo-family-events)\n**JOIN THE MAILING LIST**\nAs a small token of my appreciation, I'll also send you a FREE Japanese and English printable to help your little one learn all about words associated with spring in Japan 🌸\nThis field is required.\nCheck your inbox or spam folder to confirm your subscription.\nSearch for:\nSearch\n## Hi! I'm Kay\n![](https://tinytotintokyo.com/tokyo-family-events)\nI’m a longtime Japan resident and parent who loves writing and traveling. My goal is to help parents from around the world navigate living and traveling with kids in Japan.\n[About Me](https://tinytotintokyo.com/about-me)\n* * *\n[![](https://tinytotintokyo.com/tokyo-family-events)](https://click.jrpass.com/aff_c?offer_id=19&aff_id=1129)\n© 2026 Tiny Tot In Tokyo\n[Privacy Policy](https://tinytotintokyo.com/privacy-policy)\n_Tiny Tot In Tokyo provides information and resources about life and travel in Japan with kids, from a Japan-based parent to those around the world.  \ntinytotintokyo.com is a participant in affiliate programs such as the Amazon Services LLC Associates Program, an affiliate advertising program designed to provide a means for website owners to earn advertising fees by advertising and linking to amazon(.co.jp, .com, etc) and any other website that may be affiliated with Amazon Service LLC Associates Program. If you make a purchase using one of the links, I may receive compensation at zero additional cost to you._\n"
